    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen a buffer is reloaded due to e.g., changes outside nvim,\n* `BufRead` autocmd is executed first,\n  https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/6ef5dd5266822960d254b8acd5ab0934cc2b117e/src/nvim/fileio.c#L3146\n* and then the `on_reload` callback is invoked\n  https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/6ef5dd5266822960d254b8acd5ab0934cc2b117e/src/nvim/fileio.c#L3170\n\nThis can be problematic if `BufRead` uses treesitter functionality. Treesitter `on_reload` callback invalidates the parser state and discards the trees, which can be outdated after reload. But since `BufRead` is invoked first, the trees returned by `parse()` can still be outdated.\n\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n`repro.lua`\n```lua\nlocal started = false\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"FileType\", {\n  callback = function(ev)\n    if not started then\n      vim.treesitter.start()\n      started = true\n    end\n  end\n})\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"BufRead\", {\n  callback = function(ev)\n    if started then\n      local tree = vim.treesitter.get_parser():parse()[1]\n      vim.print({tree:root():range(false)})\n    end\n  end\n})\n```\n\n1.  ```\n    nvim --clean -u repro.lua README.md\n    ```\n2.  Remove the contents of README.md outside the nvim instance.\n3.  Focus the nvim instance.\n    It shows the range `{ 0, 0, 124, 0 }`, which is no longer valid.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n* The order of `on_reload` and `BufRead` should be specified.\n* Outdated trees should not be observable by `BufRead` and `on_reload` set up by user.\n  This could be enforced in two ways.\n    * Make `on_reload` run before `BufRead`.\n    * Invalidate parsers both on `on_reload` and `BufRead`.\n      * I can make a patch for this, but we should first discuss whether the above option is better.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 22.04\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGNOME Terminal 3.44.0 using VTE 0.68.0 +BIDI +GNUTLS +ICU +SYSTEMD\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nappimage",
